The `numtide/llm-agents.nix` flake provides two main overlays to help you integrate its packages into your own Nix configurations[1].

### Available Overlays
You can access these overlays via `llm-agents.overlays` in the flake outputs[1]:

*   **`default`**: Exposes the packages from the flake as-is, built against the flake's pinned `nixpkgs`. This ensures binary cache hits even if your own `nixpkgs` revision differs, but it requires evaluating a second `nixpkgs` instance[1].
*   **`shared-nixpkgs`**: Rebuilds each package against your own `nixpkgs`. This is more efficient for dependency sharing, but binary cache hits will only occur if your `nixpkgs` revision exactly matches the one used by the flake[1].

### Example Usage
To use the `default` overlay in a NixOS or `nix-darwin` configuration, add it to your `nixpkgs.overlays`:

```nix
{
  inputs = {
    nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixpkgs-unstable";
    llm-agents.url = "github:numtide/llm-agents.nix";
  };

  outputs = { nixpkgs, llm-agents, ... }: {
    nixosConfigurations.myhost = nixpkgs.lib.nixosSystem {
      system = "x86_64-linux";
      modules = [{
        nixpkgs.overlays = [ llm-agents.overlays.default ];

        # Now you can access packages under the llm-agents namespace
        environment.systemPackages = [
          pkgs.llm-agents.claude-code
          pkgs.llm-agents.codex
          pkgs.llm-agents.gemini-cli
        ];
      }];
    };
  };
}
```

### Binary Cache
To ensure you can use pre-built binaries (avoiding compilation from source), it is recommended to configure the Numtide binary cache in your flake or system settings[1]:

```nix
nixConfig = {
  extra-substituters = [ "https://cache.numtide.com" ];
  extra-trusted-public-keys = [ "niks3.numtide.com-1:DTx8wZduET09hRmMtKdQDxNNthLQETkc/yaX7M4qK0g=" ];
};
```

